# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: git
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:git/git-branch] If `--list` is given, or if there are no non-option arguments, existing branches are listed; the current branch will be highlighted in green and marked with an asterisk.
[src:git/git-branch] Any branches checked out in linked worktrees will be highlighted in cyan and marked with a plus sign.
[src:git/git-branch] Option `-r` causes the remote-tracking branches to be listed, and option `-a` shows both local and remote branches.
[src:git/git-branch] If a *<pattern>* is given, it is used as a shell wildcard to restrict the output to matching branches.
[src:git/git-branch] If multiple patterns are given, a branch is shown if it matches any of the patterns.
[src:git/git-branch] Note that when providing a *<pattern>*, you must use `--list`; otherwise the command may be interpreted as branch creation.
[src:git/git-branch] With `--contains`, shows only the branches that contain the named commit (in other words, the branches whose tip commits are descendants of the named commit), `--no-contains` inverts it.
[src:git/git-branch] With `--merged`, only branches merged into the named commit (i.e. the branches whose tip commits are reachable from the named commit) will be listed.
[src:git/git-branch] With `--no-merged` only branches not merged into the named commit will be listed.
[src:git/git-branch] If the *<commit>* argument is missing it defaults to `HEAD` (i.e. the tip of the current branch).
[src:git/git-branch] The command’s second form creates a new branch head named *<branch-name>* which points to the current `HEAD`, or *<start-point>* if given.
[src:git/git-branch] As a special case, for *<start-point>*, you may use *<rev-A>*`...`*<rev-B>* as a shortcut for the merge base of *<rev-A>* and *<rev-B>* if there is exactly one merge base.
[src:git/git-branch] You can leave out at most one of *<rev-A>* and *<rev-B>*, in which case it defaults to `HEAD`.
[src:git/git-branch] Note that this will create the new branch, but it will not switch the working tree to it; use `git` `switch` *<new-branch>* to switch to the new branch.
[src:git/git-branch] When a local branch is started off a remote-tracking branch, Git sets up the branch (specifically the `branch.`*<name>*`.remote` and `branch.`*<name>*`.merge` configuration entries) so that `git` `pull` will appropriately merge from the remote-tracking branch.
[src:git/git-branch] This behavior may be changed via the global `branch.autoSetupMerge` configuration flag.
[src:git/git-branch] That setting can be overridden by using the `--track` and `--no-track` options, and changed later using `git` `branch` `--set-upstream-to`.
[src:git/git-branch] With a `-m` or `-M` option, *<old-branch>* will be renamed to *<new-branch>*.
[src:git/git-branch] If *<old-branch>* had a corresponding reflog, it is renamed to match *<new-branch>*, and a reflog entry is created to remember the branch renaming.
[src:git/git-branch] If *<new-branch>* exists, `-M` must be used to force the rename to happen.
[src:git/git-branch] The `-c` and `-C` options have the exact same semantics as `-m` and `-M`, except instead of the branch being renamed, it will be copied to a new name, along with its config and reflog.
[src:git/git-branch] With a `-d` or `-D` option, *<branch-name>* will be deleted.
[src:git/git-branch] You may specify more than one branch for deletion.
[src:git/git-branch] If the branch currently has a reflog then the reflog will also be deleted.
[src:git/git-branch] Use `-r` together with `-d` to delete remote-tracking branches.
[src:git/git-branch] Note, that it only makes sense to delete remote-tracking branches if they no longer exist in the remote repository or if `git` `fetch` was configured not to fetch them again.
[src:git/git-branch] See also the `prune` subcommand of git-remote[1] for a way to clean up all obsolete remote-tracking branches.
[src:git/git-branch] The branch must be fully merged in its upstream branch, or in `HEAD` if no upstream was set with `--track` or `--set-upstream-to`.
[src:git/git-branch] This activates recording of all changes made to the branch ref, enabling use of date based sha1 expressions such as *<branch-name>*`@{yesterday}`.
[src:git/git-branch] Note that in non-bare repositories, reflogs are usually enabled by default by the `core.logAllRefUpdates` config option.
[src:git/git-branch] The negated form `--no-create-reflog` only overrides an earlier `--create-reflog`, but currently does not negate the setting of `core.logAllRefUpdates`.
[src:git/git-branch] Reset *<branch-name>* to *<start-point>*, even if *<branch-name>* exists already.
[src:git/git-branch] Without `-f`, `git` `branch` refuses to change an existing branch.
[src:git/git-branch] In combination with `-d` (or `--delete`), allow deleting the branch irrespective of its merged status, or whether it even points to a valid commit.
[src:git/git-branch] In combination with `-m` (or `--move`), allow renaming the branch even if the new branch name already exists, the same applies for `-c` (or `--copy`).
[src:git/git-branch] Note that `git` `branch` `-f` *<branch-name>* [*<start-point>*], even with `-f`, refuses to change an existing branch *<branch-name>* that is checked out in another worktree linked to the same repository.
[src:git/git-branch] Move/rename a branch, together with its config and reflog.
[src:git/git-branch] Copy a branch, together with its config and reflog.
[src:git/git-branch] Color branches to highlight current, local, and remote-tracking branches.
[src:git/git-branch] The value must be `always` (the default), `never`, or `auto`.
[src:git/git-branch] Turn off branch colors, even when the configuration file gives the default to color output.
[src:git/git-branch] Sorting and filtering branches are case insensitive.
[src:git/git-branch] Do not print a newline after formatted refs where the format expands to the empty string.
[src:git/git-branch] See configuration variable `column.branch` for option syntax.
[src:git/git-branch] `--column` and `--no-column` without options are equivalent to `always` and `never` respectively.
[src:git/git-branch] This option is only applicable in non-verbose mode.
[src:git/git-branch] Prefix `-` to sort in descending order of the value.
[src:git/git-branch] You may use the `--sort=`*<key>* option multiple times, in which case the last key becomes the primary key.
[src:git/git-branch] The keys supported are the same as those in git-for-each-ref[1].
[src:git/git-branch] Sort order defaults to the value configured for the `branch.sort` variable if it exists, or to sorting based on the full refname (including `refs/...` prefix).
[src:git/git-branch] This lists detached `HEAD` (if present) first, then local branches and finally remote-tracking branches.
[src:git/git-branch] List or delete (if used with `-d`) the remote-tracking branches.
[src:git/git-branch] Combine with `--list` to match the optional pattern(s).
[src:git/git-branch] List both remote-tracking branches and local branches.
[src:git/git-branch] Combine with `--list` to match optional pattern(s).
[src:git/git-branch] `git` `branch` `--list` `maint-*'`, list only the branches that match the pattern(s).
[src:git/git-branch] In detached `HEAD` state, nothing is printed.
[src:git/git-branch] When in list mode, show sha1 and commit subject line for each head, along with relationship to upstream branch (if any).
[src:git/git-branch] If given twice, print the path of the linked worktree (if any) and the name of the upstream branch, as well (see also `git` `remote` `show` *<remote>*).
[src:git/git-branch] Note that the current worktree’s `HEAD` will not have its path printed (it will always be your current directory).
[src:git/git-branch] Be more quiet when creating or deleting a branch, suppressing non-error messages.
[src:git/git-branch] In the verbose listing that show the commit object name, show the shortest prefix that is at least *<n>* hexdigits long that uniquely refers the object.
[src:git/git-branch] The default value is 7 and can be overridden by the `core.abbrev` config option.
[src:git/git-branch] Display the full sha1s in the output listing rather than abbreviating them.
[src:git/git-branch] When creating a new branch, set up `branch.`*<name>*`.remote` and `branch.`*<name>*`.merge` configuration entries to set "upstream" tracking configuration for the new branch.
[src:git/git-branch] This configuration will tell git to show the relationship between the two branches in `git` `status` and `git` `branch` `-v`.
[src:git/git-branch] Furthermore, it directs `git` `pull` without arguments to pull from the upstream when the new branch is checked out.
[src:git/git-branch] The exact upstream branch is chosen depending on the optional argument: `-t`, `--track`, or `--track=direct` means to use the start-point branch itself as the upstream; `--track=inherit` means to copy the upstream configuration of the start-point branch.
[src:git/git-branch] The default option, `true`, behaves as though `--track=direct` were given whenever the start-point is a remote-tracking branch.
[src:git/git-branch] `false` behaves as if `--no-track` were given.
[src:git/git-branch] `always` behaves as though `--track=direct` were given.
[src:git/git-branch] `inherit` behaves as though `--track=inherit` were given.
[src:git/git-branch] `simple` behaves as though `--track=direct` were given only when the *<start-point>* is a remote-tracking branch and the new branch has the same name as the remote branch.
[src:git/git-branch] See git-pull[1] and git-config[1] for additional discussion on how the `branch.`*<name>*`.remote` and `branch.`*<name>*`.merge` options are used.
[src:git/git-branch] Do not set up "upstream" configuration, even if the `branch.autoSetupMerge` configuration variable is set.
[src:git/git-branch] Cause the current command to recurse into submodules if `submodule.propagateBranches` is enabled.
[src:git/git-branch] See `submodule.propagateBranches` in git-config[1].
[src:git/git-branch] Currently, only branch creation is supported.
[src:git/git-branch] When used in branch creation, a new branch *<branch-name>* will be created in the superproject and all of the submodules in the superproject’s *<start-point>*.
[src:git/git-branch] In submodules, the branch will point to the submodule commit in the superproject’s *<start-point>* but the branch’s tracking information will be set up based on the submodule’s branches and remotes e.g.
[src:git/git-branch] `git` `branch` `--recurse-submodules` `topic` `origin/main` will create the submodule branch "topic" that points to the submodule commit in the superproject’s "origin/main", but tracks the submodule’s "origin/main".
[src:git/git-branch] As this option had confusing syntax, it is no longer supported.
[src:git/git-branch] Please use `--track` or `--set-upstream-to` instead.
[src:git/git-branch] Set up *<branch-name>*'s tracking information so *<upstream>* is considered *<branch-name>*'s upstream branch.
[src:git/git-branch] If no *<branch-name>* is specified, then it defaults to the current branch.
[src:git/git-branch] Remove the upstream information for *<branch-name>*.
[src:git/git-branch] If no branch is specified it defaults to the current branch.
