[src:git/git-branch] Tells `git` `branch`, `git` `switch` and `git` `checkout` to set up new branches so that git-pull[1] will appropriately merge from the starting point branch.
[src:git/git-branch] Note that even if this option is not set, this behavior can be chosen per-branch using the `--track` and `--no-track` options.
[src:git/git-branch] automatic setup is done only when the starting point is a remote-tracking branch and the new branch has the same name as the remote branch.
[src:git/git-branch] When a new branch is created with `git` `branch`, `git` `switch` or `git` `checkout` that tracks another branch, this variable tells Git to set up pull to rebase instead of merge (see `branch.`*<name>*`.rebase`).
[src:git/git-branch] rebase is never automatically set to true.
[src:git/git-branch] rebase is set to true for tracked branches of other local branches.
[src:git/git-branch] rebase is set to true for tracked branches of remote-tracking branches.
[src:git/git-branch] rebase will be set to true for all tracking branches.
[src:git/git-branch] See `branch.autoSetupMerge` for details on how to set up a branch to track another branch.
[src:git/git-branch] This variable controls the sort ordering of branches when displayed by git-branch[1].
[src:git/git-branch] Without the `--sort=`*<value>* option provided, the value of this variable will be used as the default.
[src:git/git-branch] See git-for-each-ref[1] field names for valid values.
[src:git/git-branch] When on branch *<name>*, it tells `git` `fetch` and `git` `push` which remote to fetch from or push to.
[src:git/git-branch] The remote to push to may be overridden with `remote.pushDefault` (for all branches).
[src:git/git-branch] The remote to push to, for the current branch, may be further overridden by `branch.`*<name>*`.pushRemote`.
[src:git/git-branch] If no remote is configured, or if you are not on any branch and there is more than one remote defined in the repository, it defaults to `origin` for fetching and `remote.pushDefault` for pushing.
[src:git/git-branch] Additionally, `.` (a period) is the current local repository (a dot-repository), see `branch.`*<name>*`.merge`'s final note below.
[src:git/git-branch] When on branch *<name>*, it overrides `branch.`*<name>*`.remote` for pushing.
[src:git/git-branch] It also overrides `remote.pushDefault` for pushing from branch *<name>*.
[src:git/git-branch] When you pull from one place (e.g. your upstream) and push to another place (e.g. your own publishing repository), you would want to set `remote.pushDefault` to specify the remote to push to for all branches, and use this option to override it for a specific branch.
[src:git/git-branch] Defines, together with `branch.`*<name>*`.remote`, the upstream branch for the given branch.
[src:git/git-branch] It tells `git` `fetch`/`git` `pull`/`git` `rebase` which branch to merge and can also affect `git` `push` (see `push.default`).
[src:git/git-branch] When in branch *<name>*, it tells `git` `fetch` the default refspec to be marked for merging in `FETCH_HEAD`.
[src:git/git-branch] The value is handled like the remote part of a refspec, and must match a ref which is fetched from the remote given by `branch.`*<name>*`.remote`.
[src:git/git-branch] The merge information is used by `git` `pull` (which first calls `git` `fetch`) to lookup the default branch for merging.
[src:git/git-branch] Without this option, `git` `pull` defaults to merge the first refspec fetched.
[src:git/git-branch] Specify multiple values to get an octopus merge.
[src:git/git-branch] If you wish to setup `git` `pull` so that it merges into *<name>* from another branch in the local repository, you can point `branch.`*<name>*`.merge` to the desired branch, and use the relative path setting `.` (a period) for `branch.`*<name>*`.remote`.
[src:git/git-branch] Sets default options for merging into branch *<name>*.
[src:git/git-branch] The syntax and supported options are the same as those of git-merge[1], but option values containing whitespace characters are currently not supported.
[src:git/git-branch] When true, rebase the branch *<name>* on top of the fetched branch, instead of merging the default branch from the default remote when `git` `pull` is run.
[src:git/git-branch] See `pull.rebase` for doing this in a non branch-specific manner.
[src:git/git-branch] When `merges` (or just `m`), pass the `--rebase-merges` option to `git` `rebase` so that the local merge commits are included in the rebase (see git-rebase[1] for details).
[src:git/git-branch] When the value is `interactive` (or just `i`), the rebase is run in interactive mode.
[src:git/git-branch] Branch description, can be edited with `git` `branch` `--edit-description`.
[src:git/git-branch] Branch description is automatically added to the `format-patch` cover letter or `request-pull` summary.
[src:git/git-branch] Delete the "test" branch even if the "master" branch (or whichever branch is currently checked out) does not have all commits from the test branch.
[src:git/git-branch] `for-each-ref` can take a wide range of options.
[src:git/git-checkout] See ARGUMENT DISAMBIGUATION below for how Git decides which one to do.
[src:git/git-checkout] This sets the current branch to *<branch>* and updates the files in your working directory.
[src:git/git-checkout] The checkout will fail if there are uncommitted changes to any files where *<branch>* and your current commit have different content.
[src:git/git-checkout] Uncommitted changes will otherwise be kept.
[src:git/git-checkout] Running `git` `checkout` without specifying a branch has no effect except to print out the tracking information for the current branch.
[src:git/git-checkout] Create a new branch named *<new-branch>*, start it at *<start-point>* (defaults to the current commit), and check out the new branch.
[src:git/git-checkout] You can use the `--track` or `--no-track` options to set the branch’s upstream tracking information.
[src:git/git-checkout] This will fail if there’s an error checking out *<new-branch>*, for example if checking out the *<start-point>* commit would overwrite your uncommitted changes.
[src:git/git-checkout] The same as `-b`, except that if the branch already exists it resets *<branch>* to the start point instead of failing.
[src:git/git-checkout] The same as `git` `checkout` *<branch>*, except that instead of pointing `HEAD` at the branch, it points `HEAD` at the commit ID.
[src:git/git-checkout] See the "DETACHED HEAD" section below for more.
[src:git/git-checkout] Omitting *<branch>* detaches `HEAD` at the tip of the current branch.
[src:git/git-checkout] Replace the specified files and/or directories with the version from the given commit or tree and add them to the index (also known as "staging area").
[src:git/git-checkout] For example, `git` `checkout` `main` `file.txt` will replace `file.txt` with the version from `main`.
[src:git/git-checkout] Replace the specified files and/or directories with the version from the index.
[src:git/git-checkout] For example, if you check out a commit, edit `file.txt`, and then decide those changes were a mistake, `git` `checkout` `file.txt` will discard any unstaged changes to `file.txt`.
[src:git/git-checkout] This will fail if the file has a merge conflict and you haven’t yet run `git` `add` `file.txt` (or something equivalent) to mark it as resolved.
[src:git/git-checkout] You can use `-f` to ignore the unmerged files instead of failing, use `--ours` or `--theirs` to replace them with the version from a specific side of the merge, or use `-m` to replace them with the original conflicted merge result.
[src:git/git-checkout] This is similar to the previous two modes, but lets you use the interactive interface to show the "diff" output and choose which hunks to use in the result.
[src:git/git-checkout] See below for the description of `--patch` option.
[src:git/git-checkout] Progress status is reported on the standard error stream by default when it is attached to a terminal, unless `--quiet` is specified.
[src:git/git-checkout] This flag enables progress reporting even if not attached to a terminal, regardless of `--quiet`.
[src:git/git-checkout] When switching branches, proceed even if the index or the working tree differs from `HEAD`, and even if there are untracked files in the way.
[src:git/git-checkout] This is used to throw away local changes and any untracked files or directories that are in the way.
[src:git/git-checkout] When checking out paths from the index, do not fail upon unmerged entries; instead, unmerged entries are ignored.
[src:git/git-checkout] When checking out paths from the index, check out stage #2 (`ours`) or #3 (`theirs`) for unmerged paths.
[src:git/git-checkout] Note that during `git` `rebase` and `git` `pull` `--rebase`, `ours` and `theirs` may appear swapped; `--ours` gives the version from the branch the changes are rebased onto, while `--theirs` gives the version from the branch that holds your work that is being rebased.
