[src:git/git-checkout] `checkout.defaultRemote=origin` to always checkout remote branches from there if *<branch>* is ambiguous but exists on the *origin* remote.
[src:git/git-checkout] See also `checkout.defaultRemote` in git-config[1].
[src:git/git-checkout] The default behavior can be set via the `checkout.guess` configuration variable.
[src:git/git-checkout] Create the new branch’s reflog; see git-branch[1] for details.
[src:git/git-checkout] Rather than checking out a branch to work on it, check out a commit for inspection and discardable experiments.
[src:git/git-checkout] This is the default behavior of `git` `checkout` *<commit>* when *<commit>* is not a branch name.
[src:git/git-checkout] See the "DETACHED HEAD" section below for details.
[src:git/git-checkout] Create a new unborn branch, named *<new-branch>*, started from *<start-point>* and switch to it.
[src:git/git-checkout] The first commit made on this new branch will have no parents and it will be the root of a new history totally disconnected from all the other branches and commits.
[src:git/git-checkout] The index and the working tree are adjusted as if you had previously run `git` `checkout` *<start-point>*.
[src:git/git-checkout] This allows you to start a new history that records a set of paths similar to *<start-point>* by easily running `git` `commit` `-a` to make the root commit.
[src:git/git-checkout] This can be useful when you want to publish the tree from a commit without exposing its full history.
[src:git/git-checkout] You might want to do this to publish an open source branch of a project whose current tree is "clean", but whose full history contains proprietary or otherwise encumbered bits of code.
[src:git/git-checkout] If you want to start a disconnected history that records a set of paths that is totally different from the one of *<start-point>*, then you should clear the index and the working tree right after creating the orphan branch by running `git` `rm` `-rf` `.` from the top level of the working tree.
[src:git/git-checkout] Afterwards you will be ready to prepare your new files, repopulating the working tree, by copying them from elsewhere, extracting a tarball, etc.
[src:git/git-checkout] In sparse checkout mode, `git` `checkout` `--` *<path>*... would update only entries matched by *<paths>* and sparse patterns in `$GIT_DIR/info/sparse-checkout`.
[src:git/git-checkout] This option ignores the sparse patterns and adds back any files in *<path>*....
[src:git/git-checkout] When switching branches, if you have local modifications to one or more files that are different between the current branch and the branch to which you are switching, the command refuses to switch branches in order to preserve your modifications in context.
[src:git/git-checkout] With this option, the conflicting local changes are automatically stashed before the switch and reapplied afterwards.
[src:git/git-checkout] If the local changes do not overlap with the differences between branches, the switch proceeds without stashing.
[src:git/git-checkout] If reapplying the stash results in conflicts, the entry is saved to the stash list.
[src:git/git-checkout] Resolve the conflicts and run `git` `stash` `drop` when done, or clear the working tree (e.g. with `git` `reset` `--hard`) before running `git` `stash` `pop` later to re-apply your changes.
[src:git/git-checkout] When checking out paths from the index, this option lets you recreate the conflicted merge in the specified paths.
[src:git/git-checkout] This option cannot be used when checking out paths from a tree-ish.
