[src:git/git-commit] It is *<unix-timestamp>* *<time-zone-offset>*, where *<unix-timestamp>* is the number of seconds since the UNIX epoch.
[src:git/git-commit] *<time-zone-offset>* is a positive or negative offset from UTC.
[src:git/git-commit] For example CET (which is 1 hour ahead of UTC) is `+0100`.
[src:git/git-commit] It is safer to prepend the *<unix-timestamp>* with `@` (e.g., `@0` `+0000`), which forces Git to interpret it as a raw timestamp.
[src:git/git-commit] This is required for values less than 100,000,000 (which have fewer than 9 digits) to avoid confusion with other date formats like `YYYYMMDD`.
[src:git/git-commit] The parser accepts a space instead of the `T` character as well.
[src:git/git-commit] In addition to recognizing all date formats above, the `--date` option will also try to make sense of other, more human-centric date formats, such as relative dates like "yesterday" or "last Friday at noon".
[src:git/git-commit] Though not required, it’s a good idea to begin the commit message with a single short (no more than 50 characters) line summarizing the change, followed by a blank line and then a more thorough description.
[src:git/git-commit] The text up to the first blank line in a commit message is treated as the commit title, and that title is used throughout Git.
[src:git/git-commit] For example, git-format-patch[1] turns a commit into email, and it uses the title on the Subject line and the rest of the commit in the body.
[src:git/git-commit] Git is to some extent character encoding agnostic.
[src:git/git-commit] Although we encourage that the commit log messages are encoded in UTF-8, both the core and Git Porcelain are designed not to force UTF-8 on projects.
[src:git/git-commit] If all participants of a particular project find it more convenient to use legacy encodings, Git does not forbid it.
[src:git/git-commit] However, there are a few things to keep in mind.
[src:git/git-commit] `git` `log`, `git` `show`, `git` `blame` and friends look at the `encoding` header of a commit object, and try to re-code the log message into UTF-8 unless otherwise specified.
[src:git/git-commit] You can specify the desired output encoding with `i18n.logOutputEncoding` in `.git/config` file, like this: [i18n] logOutputEncoding = ISO-8859-1 If you do not have this configuration variable, the value of `i18n.commitEncoding` is used instead.
[src:git/git-commit] Note that we deliberately chose not to re-code the commit log message when a commit is made to force UTF-8 at the commit object level, because re-coding to UTF-8 is not necessarily a reversible operation.
[src:git/git-commit] The editor used to edit the commit log message will be chosen from the `GIT_EDITOR` environment variable, the `core.editor` configuration variable, the `VISUAL` environment variable, or the `EDITOR` environment variable (in that order).
[src:git/git-commit] This setting overrides the default of the `--cleanup` option in `git` `commit`.
[src:git/git-commit] A boolean to specify whether all commits should be GPG signed.
[src:git/git-commit] Use of this option when doing operations such as rebase can result in a large number of commits being signed.
[src:git/git-commit] It may be convenient to use an agent to avoid typing your GPG passphrase several times.
[src:git/git-commit] A boolean to enable/disable inclusion of status information in the commit message template when using an editor to prepare the commit message.
[src:git/git-commit] Specify the pathname of a file to use as the template for new commit messages.
[src:git/git-commit] A boolean or int to specify the level of verbosity with `git` `commit`.
[src:git/git-commit] This command can run `commit-msg`, `prepare-commit-msg`, `pre-commit`, `post-commit` and `post-rewrite` hooks.
[src:git/git-commit] This file contains the commit message of a commit in progress.
[src:git/git-commit] If `git` `commit` exits due to an error before creating a commit, any commit message that has been provided by the user (e.g., in an editor session) will be available in this file, but will be overwritten by the next invocation of `git` `commit`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Show changes between the working tree and the index or a tree, changes between the index and a tree, changes between two trees, changes resulting from a merge, changes between two blob objects, or changes between two files on disk.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This form is to view the changes you made relative to the index (staging area for the next commit).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] In other words, the differences are what you *could* tell Git to further add to the index but you still haven’t.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] You can stage these changes by using git-add[1].
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This form is to compare the given two paths on the filesystem.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] You can omit the `--no-index` option when running the command in a working tree controlled by Git and at least one of the paths points outside the working tree, or when running the command outside a working tree controlled by Git.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] If both paths point to directories, additional pathspecs may be provided.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] These will limit the files included in the difference.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] All such pathspecs must be relative as they apply to both sides of the diff.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This form is to view the changes you staged for the next commit relative to the named *<commit>*.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Typically you would want comparison with the latest commit, so if you do not give *<commit>*, it defaults to `HEAD`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] If `HEAD` does not exist (e.g. unborn branches) and *<commit>* is not given, it shows all staged changes.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] If `--merge-base` is given, instead of using *<commit>*, use the merge base of *<commit>* and `HEAD`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This form is to view the changes you have in your working tree relative to the named *<commit>*.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] You can use `HEAD` to compare it with the latest commit, or a branch name to compare with the tip of a different branch.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This is to view the changes between two arbitrary *<commit>*.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] If `--merge-base` is given, use the merge base of the two commits for the "before" side.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This form is to view the results of a merge commit.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The first listed *<commit>* must be the merge itself; the remaining two or more commits should be its parents.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Convenient ways to produce the desired set of revisions are to use the suffixes `@` and `^!`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] If `A` is a merge commit, then `git` `diff` `A` `A^@`, `git` `diff` `A^!` and `git` `show` `A` all give the same combined diff.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This is synonymous to the earlier form (without the `..`) for viewing the changes between two arbitrary *<commit>*.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] If *<commit>* on one side is omitted, it will have the same effect as using `HEAD` instead.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This form is to view the changes on the branch containing and up to the second *<commit>*, starting at a common ancestor of both *<commit>*.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] You can omit any one of *<commit>*, which has the same effect as using `HEAD` instead.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Just in case you are doing something exotic, it should be noted that all of the *<commit>* in the above description, except in the `--merge-base` case and in the last two forms that use `..` notations, can be any *<tree>*.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] A tree of interest is the one pointed to by the ref named `AUTO_MERGE`, which is written by the `ort` merge strategy upon hitting merge conflicts (see git-merge[1]).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Comparing the working tree with `AUTO_MERGE` shows changes you’ve made so far to resolve textual conflicts (see the examples below).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] For a more complete list of ways to spell *<commit>*, see "SPECIFYING REVISIONS" section in gitrevisions[7].
[src:git/git-diff-p01] However, `diff` is about comparing two *endpoints*, not ranges, and the range notations (*<commit>*`..`*<commit>* and *<commit>*`...`*<commit>*) do not mean a range as defined in the "SPECIFYING RANGES" section in gitrevisions[7].
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This form is to view the differences between the raw contents of two blob objects.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Generate patch (see Generating patch text with -p).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Suppress all output from the diff machinery.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Useful for commands like `git` `show` that show the patch by default to squelch their output, or to cancel the effect of options like `--patch`, `--stat` earlier on the command line in an alias.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Output to a specific file instead of stdout.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Specify the character used to indicate new, old or context lines in the generated patch.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Normally they are `+`, `-` and ' ' respectively.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Enable the heuristic that shifts diff hunk boundaries to make patches easier to read.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Spend extra time to make sure the smallest possible diff is produced.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Generate a diff using the "patience diff" algorithm.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Generate a diff using the "histogram diff" algorithm.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Generate a diff using the "anchored diff" algorithm.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This option may be specified more than once.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] If a line exists in both the source and destination, exists only once, and starts with *<text>*, this algorithm attempts to prevent it from appearing as a deletion or addition in the output.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] It uses the "patience diff" algorithm internally.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Use "patience diff" algorithm when generating patches.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This algorithm extends the patience algorithm to "support low-occurrence common elements".
[src:git/git-diff-p01] For instance, if you configured the `diff.algorithm` variable to a non-default value and want to use the default one, then you have to use `--diff-algorithm=default` option.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] By default, as much space as necessary will be used for the filename part, and the rest for the graph part.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Maximum width defaults to terminal width, or 80 columns if not connected to a terminal, and can be overridden by *<width>*.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The width of the filename part can be limited by giving another width *<name-width>* after a comma or by setting `diff.statNameWidth=`*<name-width>*.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The width of the graph part can be limited by using `--stat-graph-width=`*<graph-width>* or by setting `diff.statGraphWidth=`*<graph-width>*.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Using `--stat` or `--stat-graph-width` affects all commands generating a stat graph, while setting `diff.statNameWidth` or `diff.statGraphWidth` does not affect `git` `format-patch`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] By giving a third parameter *<count>*, you can limit the output to the first *<count>* lines, followed by ... if there are more.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] These parameters can also be set individually with `--stat-width=`*<width>*, `--stat-name-width=`*<name-width>* and `--stat-count=`*<count>*.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Output a condensed summary of extended header information such as file creations or deletions ("new" or "gone", optionally `+l` if it’s a symlink) and mode changes (`+x` or `-x` for adding or removing executable bit respectively) in diffstat.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The information is put between the filename part and the graph part.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Similar to `--stat`, but shows number of added and deleted lines in decimal notation and pathname without abbreviation, to make it more machine friendly.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] For binary files, outputs two `-` instead of saying `0` `0`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Output only the last line of the `--stat` format containing total number of modified files, as well as number of added and deleted lines.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Output the distribution of relative amount of changes for each sub-directory.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The behavior of `--dirstat` can be customized by passing it a comma separated list of parameters.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The defaults are controlled by the `diff.dirstat` configuration variable (see git-config[1]).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Compute the dirstat numbers by counting the lines that have been removed from the source, or added to the destination.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This ignores the amount of pure code movements within a file.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] In other words, rearranging lines in a file is not counted as much as other changes.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This is the default behavior when no parameter is given.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Compute the dirstat numbers by doing the regular line-based diff analysis, and summing the removed/added line counts.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] (For binary files, count 64-byte chunks instead, since binary files have no natural concept of lines).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This is a more expensive `--dirstat` behavior than the `changes` behavior, but it does count rearranged lines within a file as much as other changes.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The resulting output is consistent with what you get from the other `--*stat` options.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Compute the dirstat numbers by counting the number of files changed.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Each changed file counts equally in the dirstat analysis.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This is the computationally cheapest `--dirstat` behavior, since it does not have to look at the file contents at all.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Count changes in a child directory for the parent directory as well.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Note that when using `cumulative`, the sum of the percentages reported may exceed 100%.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The default (non-cumulative) behavior can be specified with the `noncumulative` parameter.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] An integer parameter specifies a cut-off percent (3% by default).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Directories contributing less than this percentage of the changes are not shown in the output.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Example: The following will count changed files, while ignoring directories with less than 10% of the total amount of changed files, and accumulating child directory counts in the parent directories: `--dirstat=files,10,cumulative`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Output a condensed summary of extended header information such as creations, renames and mode changes.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] When `--raw`, `--numstat`, `--name-only` or `--name-status` has been given, do not munge pathnames and use NULs as output field terminators.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Without this option, pathnames with "unusual" characters are quoted as explained for the configuration variable `core.quotePath` (see git-config[1]).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Show only the name of each changed file in the post-image tree.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The file names are often encoded in UTF-8.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] For more information see the discussion about encoding in the git-log[1] manual page.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Show only the name(s) and status of each changed file.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] See the description of the `--diff-filter` option on what the status letters mean.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Just like `--name-only` the file names are often encoded in UTF-8.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Specify how differences in submodules are shown.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] When specifying `--submodule=short` the `short` format is used.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This format just shows the names of the commits at the beginning and end of the range.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] When `--submodule` or `--submodule=log` is specified, the `log` format is used.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This format lists the commits in the range like git-submodule[1] `summary` does.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] When `--submodule=diff` is specified, the `diff` format is used.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This format shows an inline diff of the changes in the submodule contents between the commit range.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Defaults to `diff.submodule` or the `short` format if the config option is unset.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] *<when>* can be one of `always`, `never`, or `auto`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] It can be changed by the `color.ui` and `color.diff` configuration settings.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This can be used to override configuration settings.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Moved lines of code are colored differently.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] It can be changed by the `diff.colorMoved` configuration setting.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The *<mode>* defaults to `no` if the option is not given and to `zebra` if the option with no mode is given.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This may change to a more sensible mode in the future.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Any line that is added in one location and was removed in another location will be colored with `color.diff.newMoved`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Similarly `color.diff.oldMoved` will be used for removed lines that are added somewhere else in the diff.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This mode picks up any moved line, but it is not very useful in a review to determine if a block of code was moved without permutation.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Blocks of moved text of at least 20 alphanumeric characters are detected greedily.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The detected blocks are painted using either the `color.diff.`(`old`|`new`)`Moved` color.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Blocks of moved text are detected as in `blocks` mode.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The blocks are painted using either the `color.diff.`(`old`|`new`)`Moved` color or `color.diff.`(`old`|`new`)`MovedAlternative`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The change between the two colors indicates that a new block was detected.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Similar to `zebra`, but additional dimming of uninteresting parts of moved code is performed.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The bordering lines of two adjacent blocks are considered interesting, the rest is uninteresting.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This configures how whitespace is ignored when performing the move detection for `--color-moved`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] It can be set by the `diff.colorMovedWS` configuration setting.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Do not ignore whitespace when performing move detection.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This ignores whitespace at line end, and considers all other sequences of one or more whitespace characters to be equivalent.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This ignores differences even if one line has whitespace where the other line has none.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Initially ignore any whitespace in the move detection, then group the moved code blocks only into a block if the change in whitespace is the same per line.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This is incompatible with the other modes.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] It is the same as `--color-moved-ws=no`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] By default, words are delimited by whitespace; see `--word-diff-regex` below.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Highlight changed words using only colors.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Show words as [`-removed-`] and {`added`}.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Makes no attempts to escape the delimiters if they appear in the input, so the output may be ambiguous.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Use a special line-based format intended for script consumption.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Added/removed/unchanged runs are printed in the usual unified diff format, starting with a `+`/`-`/` ` character at the beginning of the line and extending to the end of the line.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Newlines in the input are represented by a tilde `~` on a line of its own.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Note that despite the name of the first mode, color is used to highlight the changed parts in all modes if enabled.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The `--word-diff` option operates by taking the same line-by-line diff that is produced without the option and computing word-by-word changes within each hunk.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This may produce a larger diff than a dedicated word-diff tool would.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] If Git acquires a different implementation in the future, the output may change.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Note that this is similar to the `--diff-algorithm` option, which may also change the output.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Use *<regex>* to decide what a word is, instead of considering runs of non-whitespace to be a word.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Also implies `--word-diff` unless it was already enabled.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Every non-overlapping match of the *<regex>* is considered a word.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Anything between these matches is considered whitespace and ignored(!) for the purposes of finding differences.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] You may want to append |[`^`[`:space:`]] to your regular expression to make sure that it matches all non-whitespace characters.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] A match that contains a newline is silently truncated(!) at the newline.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] For example, `--word-diff-regex=.` will treat each character as a word and, correspondingly, show differences character by character.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The regex can also be set via a diff driver or configuration option, see gitattributes[5] or git-config[1].
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Giving it explicitly overrides any diff driver or configuration setting.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Diff drivers override configuration settings.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Equivalent to `--word-diff=color` plus (if a regex was specified) `--word-diff-regex=`*<regex>*.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Turn off rename detection, even when the configuration file gives the default to do so.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Whether to use empty blobs as rename source.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Warn if changes introduce conflict markers or whitespace errors.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] What are considered whitespace errors is controlled by `core.whitespace` configuration.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] By default, trailing whitespaces (including lines that consist solely of whitespaces) and a space character that is immediately followed by a tab character inside the initial indent of the line are considered whitespace errors.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Exits with non-zero status if problems are found.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Highlight whitespace errors in the `context`, `old` or `new` lines of the diff.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Multiple values are separated by comma, `none` resets previous values, `default` reset the list to `new` and `all` is a shorthand for `old,new,context`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] When this option is not given, and the configuration variable `diff.wsErrorHighlight` is not set, only whitespace errors in `new` lines are highlighted.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The whitespace errors are colored with `color.diff.whitespace`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Instead of the first handful of characters, show the full pre- and post-image blob object names on the "index" line when generating patch format output.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] In addition to `--full-index`, output a binary diff that can be applied with `git-apply`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Instead of showing the full 40-byte hexadecimal object name in diff-raw format output and diff-tree header lines, show the shortest prefix that is at least *<n>* hexdigits long that uniquely refers the object.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] In diff-patch output format, `--full-index` takes higher precedence, i.e. if `--full-index` is specified, full blob names will be shown regardless of `--abbrev`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Non default number of digits can be specified with `--abbrev=`*<n>*.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Break complete rewrite changes into pairs of delete and create.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] `-B/70%` specifies that less than 30% of the original should remain in the result for Git to consider it a total rewrite (i.e. otherwise the resulting patch will be a series of deletion and insertion mixed together with context lines).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] When used with `-M`, a totally-rewritten file is also considered as the source of a rename (usually `-M` only considers a file that disappeared as the source of a rename), and the number *<n>* controls this aspect of the `-B` option (defaults to 50%).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] `-B20%` specifies that a change with addition and deletion compared to 20% or more of the file’s size are eligible for being picked up as a possible source of a rename to another file.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] If *<n>* is specified, it is a threshold on the similarity index (i.e. amount of addition/deletions compared to the file’s size).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] For example, `-M90%` means Git should consider a delete/add pair to be a rename if more than 90% of the file hasn’t changed.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Without a `%` sign, the number is to be read as a fraction, with a decimal point before it.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] To limit detection to exact renames, use `-M100%`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] If *<n>* is specified, it has the same meaning as for `-M`*<n>*.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] For performance reasons, by default, `-C` option finds copies only if the original file of the copy was modified in the same changeset.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This flag makes the command inspect unmodified files as candidates for the source of copy.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This is a very expensive operation for large projects, so use it with caution.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Giving more than one `-C` option has the same effect.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Omit the preimage for deletes, i.e. print only the header but not the diff between the preimage and `/dev/null`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The resulting patch is not meant to be applied with `patch` or `git` `apply`; this is solely for people who want to just concentrate on reviewing the text after the change.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] In addition, the output obviously lacks enough information to apply such a patch in reverse, even manually, hence the name of the option.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] When used together with `-B`, omit also the preimage in the deletion part of a delete/create pair.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The `-M` and `-C` options involve some preliminary steps that can detect subsets of renames/copies cheaply, followed by an exhaustive fallback portion that compares all remaining unpaired destinations to all relevant sources.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] (For renames, only remaining unpaired sources are relevant; for copies, all original sources are relevant.) For N sources and destinations, this exhaustive check is O(N^2).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This option prevents the exhaustive portion of rename/copy detection from running if the number of source/destination files involved exceeds the specified number.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Note that a value of 0 is treated as unlimited.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Select only files that are Added (`A`), Copied (`C`), Deleted (`D`), Modified (`M`), Renamed (`R`), have their type (i.e. regular file, symlink, submodule, …) changed (`T`), are Unmerged (`U`), are Unknown (`X`), or have had their pairing Broken (`B`).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Any combination of the filter characters (including none) can be used.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] When `*` (All-or-none) is added to the combination, all paths are selected if there is any file that matches other criteria in the comparison; if there is no file that matches other criteria, nothing is selected.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Also, these upper-case letters can be downcased to exclude.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] `--diff-filter=ad` excludes added and deleted paths.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Note that not all diffs can feature all types.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] For instance, copied and renamed entries cannot appear if detection for those types is disabled.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Look for differences that change the number of occurrences of the specified *<string>* (i.e. addition/deletion) in a file.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Look for differences whose patch text contains added/removed lines that match *<regex>*.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] While *git log -G"frotz\(nitfol"* will show this commit, *git log* *-S"frotz\(nitfol" --pickaxe-regex* will not (because the number of occurrences of that string did not change).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Unless `--text` is supplied patches of binary files without a textconv filter will be ignored.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] See the *pickaxe* entry in gitdiffcore[7] for more information.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Look for differences that change the number of occurrences of the specified object.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Similar to `-S`, just the argument is different in that it doesn’t search for a specific string but for a specific object id.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The object can be a blob or a submodule commit.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] It implies the `-t` option in `git-log` to also find trees.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] When `-S` or `-G` finds a change, show all the changes in that changeset, not just the files that contain the change in *<string>*.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Treat the *<string>* given to `-S` as an extended POSIX regular expression to match.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Control the order in which files appear in the output.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This overrides the `diff.orderFile` configuration variable (see git-config[1]).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] To cancel `diff.orderFile`, use `-O/dev/null`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The output order is determined by the order of glob patterns in *<orderfile>*.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] All files with pathnames that match the first pattern are output first, all files with pathnames that match the second pattern (but not the first) are output next, and so on.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] All files with pathnames that do not match any pattern are output last, as if there was an implicit match-all pattern at the end of the file.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] If multiple pathnames have the same rank (they match the same pattern but no earlier patterns), their output order relative to each other is the normal order.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Patterns have the same syntax and semantics as patterns used for `fnmatch`(3) without the `FNM_PATHNAME` flag, except a pathname also matches a pattern if removing any number of the final pathname components matches the pattern.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] For example, the pattern "`foo*bar`" matches "`fooasdfbar`" and "`foo/bar/baz/asdf`" but not "`foobarx`".
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Discard the files before the named *<file>* from the output (i.e.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] *skip to*), or move them to the end of the output (i.e.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] These options were invented primarily for the use of the `git` `difftool` command, and may not be very useful otherwise.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Swap two inputs; that is, show differences from index or on-disk file to tree contents.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] When run from a subdirectory of the project, it can be told to exclude changes outside the directory and show pathnames relative to it with this option.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] When you are not in a subdirectory (e.g. in a bare repository), you can name which subdirectory to make the output relative to by giving a *<path>* as an argument.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] `--no-relative` can be used to countermand both `diff.relative` config option and previous `--relative`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Ignore carriage-return at the end of line when doing a comparison.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Ignore changes whose lines are all blank.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Ignore changes whose all lines match *<regex>*.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Show whole function as context lines for each change.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The function names are determined in the same way as `git` `diff` works out patch hunk headers (see "Defining a custom hunk-header" in gitattributes[5]).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Make the program exit with codes similar to `diff`(1).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] That is, it exits with 1 if there were differences and 0 means no differences.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Disables execution of external diff helpers whose exit code is not trusted, i.e. their respective configuration option `diff.trustExitCode` or `diff.`*<driver>*`.trustExitCode` or environment variable `GIT_EXTERNAL_DIFF_TRUST_EXIT_CODE` is false.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Allow an external diff helper to be executed.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] If you set an external diff driver with gitattributes[5], you need to use this option with git-log[1] and friends.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Allow (or disallow) external text conversion filters to be run when comparing binary files.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Because textconv filters are typically a one-way conversion, the resulting diff is suitable for human consumption, but cannot be applied.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] For this reason, textconv filters are enabled by default only for git-diff[1] and git-log[1], but not for git-format-patch[1] or diff plumbing commands.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Ignore changes to submodules in the diff generation.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Using `none` will consider the submodule modified when it either contains untracked or modified files or its `HEAD` differs from the commit recorded in the superproject and can be used to override any settings of the `ignore` option in git-config[1] or gitmodules[5].
[src:git/git-diff-p01] When `untracked` is used submodules are not considered dirty when they only contain untracked content (but they are still scanned for modified content).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Using `dirty` ignores all changes to the work tree of submodules, only changes to the commits stored in the superproject are shown (this was the behavior until 1.7.0).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Using `all` hides all changes to submodules.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Show the given source *<prefix>* instead of "a/".
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Show the given destination *<prefix>* instead of "b/".
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Do not show any source or destination prefix.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Use the default source and destination prefixes ("a/" and "b/").
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This overrides configuration variables such as `diff.noprefix`, `diff.srcPrefix`, `diff.dstPrefix`, and `diff.mnemonicPrefix` (see git-config[1]).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Prepend an additional *<prefix>* to every line of output.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] By default entries added by `git` `add` `-N` appear as an existing empty file in `git` `diff` and a new file in `git` `diff` `--cached`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This option makes the entry appear as a new file in `git` `diff` and non-existent in `git` `diff` `--cached`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This option could be reverted with `--ita-visible-in-index`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Both options are experimental and could be removed in future.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] For each pathspec given on command line, descend at most *<depth>* levels of directories.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Cannot be combined with wildcards in the pathspec.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] If no pathspec is given, the depth is measured as if all top-level entries were specified.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Note that this is different than measuring from the root, in that `--max-depth=0` would still return `foo`.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] This allows you to still limit depth while asking for a subset of the top-level entries.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Note that this option is only supported for diffs between tree objects, not against the index or working tree.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] For more detailed explanation on these common options, see also gitdiffcore[7].
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The index contains these stages only for unmerged entries i.e. while resolving conflicts.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] See git-read-tree[1] section "3-Way Merge" for detailed information.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Omit diff output for unmerged entries and just show "Unmerged".
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Can be used only when comparing the working tree with the index.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The *<path>* parameters, when given, are used to limit the diff to the named paths (you can give directory names and get diff for all files under them).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The raw output format from `git-diff-index`, `git-diff-tree`, `git-diff-files` and `git` `diff` `--raw` are very similar.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] compares the *<tree-ish>* and the files on the filesystem.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] compares the *<tree-ish>* and the index.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] compares the trees named by the two arguments.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] compares the index and the files on the filesystem.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] All the commands print one output line per changed file, except `git` `diff-files` in the case of an unmerged file, which prints both an "unmerged" and an "in-place edit" line.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] 2. mode for "src"; 000000 if creation, or if "src" is from the index and is unmerged.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] 4. mode for "dst"; 000000 if deletion, or if "dst" is from the index and is unmerged.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] 6. sha1 for "src"; 0{40} if creation, or if "src" is from the index and is unmerged.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] 8. sha1 for "dst"; 0{40} if deletion, if "dst" is from the index and is unmerged, or if "dst" is from the work tree and is out of sync with the index.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] 10. status, followed by optional "score" number.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] 11. a tab or a NUL when `-z` option is used.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] 13. a tab or a NUL when `-z` option is used; only exists for C or R.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] 14. path for "dst"; only exists for C or R.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] 15. an LF or a NUL when `-z` option is used, to terminate the record.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Status letters `C` and `R` are always followed by a score (denoting the percentage of similarity between the source and target of the move or copy).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Status letter `M` may be followed by a score (denoting the percentage of dissimilarity) for file rewrites.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The sha1 for "dst" is shown as all 0’s if a file on the filesystem is out of sync with the index.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Without the `-z` option, pathnames with "unusual" characters are quoted as explained for the configuration variable `core.quotePath` (see git-config[1]).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Using `-z` the filename is output verbatim and the line is terminated by a NUL byte.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] `git-diff-tree`, `git-diff-files` and `git-diff` `--raw` can take `-c` or `--cc` option to generate diff output also for merge commits.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] For `-c` and `--cc`, only the destination or final path is shown even if the file was renamed on any side of history.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] With `--combined-all-paths`, the name of the path in each parent is shown followed by the name of the path in the merge commit.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Note that *combined diff* lists only files which were modified from all parents.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Running git-diff[1], git-log[1], git-show[1], git-diff-index[1], git-diff-tree[1], or git-diff-files[1] with the `-p` option produces patch text.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] You can customize the creation of patch text via the `GIT_EXTERNAL_DIFF` and the `GIT_DIFF_OPTS` environment variables (see git[1]), and the `diff` attribute (see gitattributes[5]).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Path names in extended headers do not include the `a/` and `b/` prefixes.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The similarity index is the percentage of unchanged lines, and the dissimilarity index is the percentage of changed lines.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] It is a rounded down integer, followed by a percent sign.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The similarity index value of 100% is thus reserved for two equal files, while 100% dissimilarity means that no line from the old file made it into the new one.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The index line includes the blob object names before and after the change.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] The *<mode>* is included if the file mode does not change; otherwise, separate lines indicate the old and the new mode.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Pathnames with "unusual" characters are quoted as explained for the configuration variable `core.quotePath` (see git-config[1]).
[src:git/git-diff-p01] All the `file1` files in the output refer to files before the commit, and all the `file2` files refer to files after the commit.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] It is incorrect to apply each change to each file sequentially.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] Hunk headers mention the name of the function to which the hunk applies.
[src:git/git-diff-p01] See "Defining a custom hunk-header" in gitattributes[5] for details of how to tailor this to specific languages.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Any diff-generating command can take the `-c` or `--cc` option to produce a *combined diff* when showing a merge.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] This is the default format when showing merges with git-diff[1] or git-show[1].
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Note also that you can give suitable `--diff-merges` option to any of these commands to force generation of diffs in a specific format.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Extended headers with information about detected content movement (renames and copying detection) are designed to work with the diff of two *<tree-ish>* and are not used by combined diff format.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] It is followed by a two-line from-file/to-file header: --- a/file +++ b/file Similar to the two-line header for the traditional *unified* diff format, `/dev/null` is used to signal created or deleted files.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Chunk header format is modified to prevent people from accidentally feeding it to `patch` `-p1`.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Combined diff format was created for review of merge commit changes, and was not meant to be applied.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] The change is similar to the change in the extended *index* header: @@@ <from-file-range> <from-file-range> <to-file-range> @@@ There are (number of parents + 1) `@` characters in the chunk header for combined diff format.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] One column for each of fileN is prepended to the output line to note how X’s line is different from it.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] A `-` character in the column N means that the line appears in fileN but it does not appear in the result.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] A `+` character in the column N means that the line appears in the result, and fileN does not have that line (in other words, the line was added, from the point of view of that parent).
[src:git/git-diff-p02] In the above example output, the function signature was changed from both files (hence two `-` removals from both file1 and file2, plus `++` to mean one line that was added does not appear in either file1 or file2).
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Also, eight other lines are the same from file1 but do not appear in file2 (hence prefixed with `+`).
[src:git/git-diff-p02] When shown by `git` `diff-tree` `-c`, it compares the parents of a merge commit with the merge result (i.e. file1..fileN are the parents).
[src:git/git-diff-p02] When shown by `git` `diff-files` `-c`, it compares the two unresolved merge parents with the working tree file (i.e. file1 is stage 2 aka "our version", file2 is stage 3 aka "their version").
[src:git/git-diff-p02] The `--summary` option describes newly added, deleted, renamed and copied files.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] The `--stat` option adds `diffstat`(1) graph to the output.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] These options can be combined with other options, such as `-p`, and are meant for human consumption.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] When showing a change that involves a rename or a copy, `--stat` output formats the pathnames compactly by combining common prefix and suffix of the pathnames.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] The `--numstat` option gives the diffstat(1) information but is designed for easier machine consumption.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] The extra `NUL` before the preimage path in renamed case is to allow scripts that read the output to tell if the current record being read is a single-path record or a rename/copy record without reading ahead.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] After reading added and deleted lines, reading up to `NUL` would yield the pathname, but if that is `NUL`, the record will show two paths.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Changes between the index and your last commit; what you would be committing if you run `git` `commit` without `-a` option.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Changes in the working tree you’ve made to resolve textual conflicts so far.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Instead of comparing with the tip of "test" branch, compare with the tip of the current branch, but limit the comparison to the file "test".
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Compare the version before the last commit and the last commit.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Changes that occurred on the master branch since when the topic branch was started off it.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Show only names and the nature of change, but not actual diff output.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] When using `git` `diff` to compare with work tree files, do not consider stat-only changes as changed.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Instead, silently run `git` `update-index` `--refresh` to update the cached stat information for paths whose contents in the work tree match the contents in the index.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Note that this affects only `git` `diff` Porcelain, and not lower level `diff` commands such as `git` `diff-files`.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] A comma separated list of `--dirstat` parameters specifying the default behavior of the `--dirstat` option to `git` `diff` and friends.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] The defaults can be overridden on the command line (using `--dirstat=`*<param>*`,...`).
[src:git/git-diff-p02] The fallback defaults (when not changed by `diff.dirstat`) are `changes,noncumulative,3`.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Example: The following will count changed files, while ignoring directories with less than 10% of the total amount of changed files, and accumulating child directory counts in the parent directories: `files,10,cumulative`.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Limit the width of the filename part in `--stat` output.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] If set, applies to all commands generating `--stat` output except `format-patch`.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Limit the width of the graph part in `--stat` output.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Generate diffs with *<n>* lines of context instead of the default of 3.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] This value is overridden by the `-U` option.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Show the context between diff hunks, up to the specified number of lines, thereby fusing the hunks that are close to each other.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] This value serves as the default for the `--inter-hunk-context` command line option.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] If this config variable is set, diff generation is not performed using the internal diff machinery, but using the given command.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Can be overridden with the `GIT_EXTERNAL_DIFF` environment variable.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] The command is called with parameters as described under "git Diffs" in git[1].
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Note: if you want to use an external diff program only on a subset of your files, you might want to use gitattributes[5] instead.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] If this boolean value is set to `true` then the `diff.external` command is expected to return exit code 0 if it considers the input files to be equal or 1 if it considers them to be different, like `diff`(1).
[src:git/git-diff-p02] If it is set to `false`, which is the default, then the command is expected to return exit code `0` regardless of equality.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Any other exit code causes Git to report a fatal error.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Sets the default value of `--ignore-submodules`.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] `git` `checkout` and `git` `switch` also honor this setting when reporting uncommitted changes.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Setting it to `all` disables the submodule summary normally shown by `git` `commit` and `git` `status` when `status.submoduleSummary` is set unless it is overridden by using the `--ignore-submodules` command-line option.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] The `git` `submodule` commands are not affected by this setting.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] By default this is set to untracked so that any untracked submodules are ignored.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] If set, `git` `diff` uses a prefix pair that is different from the standard `a/` and `b/` depending on what is being compared.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] compares two non-git things *<a>* and *<b>*.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] If set, `git` `diff` does not show any source or destination prefix.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] If set, `git` `diff` uses this source prefix.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] If set, `git` `diff` uses this destination prefix.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] If set to `true`, `git` `diff` does not show changes outside of the directory and show pathnames relative to the current directory.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] File indicating how to order files within a diff.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] If `diff.orderFile` is a relative pathname, it is treated as relative to the top of the working tree.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] The number of files to consider in the exhaustive portion of copy/rename detection; equivalent to the `git` `diff` option `-l`.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] If not set, the default value is currently 1000.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] This setting has no effect if rename detection is turned off.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] If set to `false`, rename detection is disabled.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] If set to `true`, basic rename detection is enabled.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] If set to `copies` or `copy`, Git will detect copies, as well.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Note that this affects only `git` `diff` Porcelain like git-diff[1] and git-log[1], and not lower level commands such as git-diff-files[1].
[src:git/git-diff-p02] A boolean to inhibit the standard behavior of printing a space before each empty output line.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Specify the format in which differences in submodules are shown.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] The `short` format just shows the names of the commits at the beginning and end of the range.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] The `log` format lists the commits in the range like git-submodule[1] `summary` does.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] The `diff` format shows an inline diff of the changed contents of the submodule.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] A POSIX Extended Regular Expression used to determine what is a "word" when performing word-by-word difference calculations.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Character sequences that match the regular expression are "words", all other characters are **ignorable** whitespace.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] If this boolean value is set to `true` then the `diff.`*<driver>*`.command` command is expected to return exit code 0 if it considers the input files to be equal or 1 if it considers them to be different, like `diff`(1).
[src:git/git-diff-p02] If it is set to `false`, which is the default, then the command is expected to return exit code 0 regardless of equality.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] The regular expression that the diff driver should use to recognize the hunk header.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Set this option to `true` to make the diff driver treat files as binary.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] The command that the diff driver should call to generate the text-converted version of a file.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] The result of the conversion is used to generate a human-readable diff.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] The regular expression that the diff driver should use to split words in a line.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Set this option to `true` to make the diff driver cache the text conversion outputs.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] Set this option to `false` to disable the default heuristics that shift diff hunk boundaries to make patches easier to read.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] The command line option `--ws-error-highlight=`*<kind>* overrides this setting.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] If set to either a valid *<mode>* or a `true` value, moved lines in a diff are colored differently.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] For details of valid modes see `--color-moved`.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] If simply set to `true` the default color mode will be used.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] When set to `false`, moved lines are not colored.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] When moved lines are colored using e.g. the `diff.colorMoved` setting, this option controls the mode how spaces are treated.
[src:git/git-diff-p02] For details of valid modes see `--color-moved-ws` in git-diff[1].
[src:git/git-log-p01] List commits that are reachable by following the `parent` links from the given commit(s), but exclude commits that are reachable from the one(s) given with a *^* in front of them.
[src:git/git-log-p01] The output is given in reverse chronological order by default.
[src:git/git-log-p01] You can think of this as a set operation.
[src:git/git-log-p01] Commits reachable from any of the commits given on the command line form a set, and then commits reachable from any of the ones given with *^* in front are subtracted from that set.
[src:git/git-log-p01] The remaining commits are what comes out in the command’s output.
[src:git/git-log-p01] Various other options and paths parameters can be used to further limit the result.
[src:git/git-log-p01] means "list all the commits which are reachable from *foo* or *bar*, but not from *baz*".
[src:git/git-log-p01] Another special notation is "*<commit1>*`...`*<commit2>*" which is useful for merges.
[src:git/git-log-p01] The resulting set of commits is the symmetric difference between the two operands.
[src:git/git-log-p01] The command takes options applicable to the git-rev-list[1] command to control what is shown and how, and options applicable to the git-diff[1] command to control how the changes each commit introduces are shown.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Continue listing the history of a file beyond renames (works only for a single file).
[src:git/git-log-p02] Print out the ref names of any commits that are shown.
[src:git/git-log-p02] the ref name prefixes `refs/heads/`, `refs/tags/` and `refs/remotes/` are not printed.
[src:git/git-log-p02] the full ref name (including prefix) is printed.
[src:git/git-log-p02] if the output is going to a terminal, the ref names are shown as if `short` were given, otherwise no ref names are shown.
[src:git/git-log-p02] The option `--decorate` is short-hand for `--decorate=short`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Default to configuration value of `log.decorate` if configured, otherwise, `auto`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] For each candidate reference, do not use it for decoration if it matches any of the *<pattern>* parameters given to `--decorate-refs-exclude` or if it doesn’t match any of the *<pattern>* parameters given to `--decorate-refs`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] The `log.excludeDecoration` config option allows excluding refs from the decorations, but an explicit `--decorate-refs` pattern will override a match in `log.excludeDecoration`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] If none of these options or config settings are given, then references are used as decoration if they match `HEAD`, `refs/heads/`, `refs/remotes/`, `refs/stash/`, or `refs/tags/`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] When specified, this option clears all previous `--decorate-refs` or `--decorate-refs-exclude` options and relaxes the default decoration filter to include all references.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This option is assumed if the config value `log.initialDecorationSet` is set to `all`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Print out the ref name given on the command line by which each commit was reached.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Use mailmap file to map author and committer names and email addresses to canonical real names and email addresses.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Without this flag, `git` `log` `-p` *<path>*... shows commits that touch the specified paths, and diffs about the same specified paths.
[src:git/git-log-p02] With this, the full diff is shown for commits that touch the specified paths; this means that "*<path>*..." limits only commits, and doesn’t limit diff for those commits.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Note that this affects all diff-based output types, e.g. those produced by `--stat`, etc.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Include a line `log` `size` *<number>* in the output for each commit, where *<number>* is the length of that commit’s message in bytes.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Intended to speed up tools that read log messages from `git` `log` output by allowing them to allocate space in advance.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Trace the evolution of the line range given by *<start>*`,`*<end>*, or by the function name regex *<funcname>*, within the *<file>*.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This is currently limited to a walk starting from a single revision, i.e., you may only give zero or one positive revision arguments, and *<start>* and *<end>* (or *<funcname>*) must exist in the starting revision.
[src:git/git-log-p02] You can specify this option more than once.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Patch output can be suppressed using `--no-patch`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Non-patch diff formats `--raw`, `--name-only`, `--name-status`, and `--summary` are supported.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Diff stat formats (`--stat`, `--numstat`, `--shortstat`, `--dirstat`) are not currently implemented.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Patch formatting options such as `--word-diff`, `--color-moved`, `--no-prefix`, and whitespace options (`-w`, `-b`) are supported, as are pickaxe options (`-S`, `-G`) and `--diff-filter`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] If `:`*<funcname>* is given in place of *<start>* and *<end>*, it is a regular expression that denotes the range from the first funcname line that matches *<funcname>*, up to the next funcname line.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `:`*<funcname>* searches from the end of the previous `-L` range, if any, otherwise from the start of file.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `^:`*<funcname>* searches from the start of file.
[src:git/git-log-p02] The function names are determined in the same way as `git` `diff` works out patch hunk headers (see *Defining a custom hunk-header* in gitattributes[5]).
[src:git/git-log-p02] Show only commits in the specified revision range.
[src:git/git-log-p02] When no *<revision-range>* is specified, it defaults to `HEAD` (i.e. the whole history leading to the current commit).
