[src:git/git-log-p02] Limit the commits output to ones with reflog entries that match the *<pattern>* regular expression.
[src:git/git-log-p02] With more than one `--grep-reflog`, commits whose reflog message matches any of the given patterns are chosen.
[src:git/git-log-p02] It is an error to use this option unless `--walk-reflogs` is in use.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Limit the commits output to ones with a log message that matches the *<pattern>* regular expression.
[src:git/git-log-p02] With more than one `--grep=`*<pattern>*, commits whose message matches any of the *<pattern>* are chosen (but see `--all-match`).
[src:git/git-log-p02] When `--notes` is in effect, the message from the notes is matched as if it were part of the log message.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Limit the commits output to ones that match all given `--grep`, instead of ones that match at least one.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Limit the commits output to ones with a log message that do not match the *<pattern>* specified with `--grep=`*<pattern>*.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Match the regular expression limiting patterns without regard to letter case.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Consider the limiting patterns to be basic regular expressions; this is the default.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Consider the limiting patterns to be extended regular expressions instead of the default basic regular expressions.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Consider the limiting patterns to be fixed strings (don’t interpret pattern as a regular expression).
[src:git/git-log-p02] Consider the limiting patterns to be Perl-compatible regular expressions.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Support for these types of regular expressions is an optional compile-time dependency.
[src:git/git-log-p02] If Git wasn’t compiled with support for them providing this option will cause it to die.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Stop when a given path disappears from the tree.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This is exactly the same as `--min-parents=2`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Do not print commits with more than one parent.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This is exactly the same as `--max-parents=1`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Show only commits which have at least (or at most) that many parent commits.
[src:git/git-log-p02] In particular, `--max-parents=1` is the same as `--no-merges`, `--min-parents=2` is the same as `--merges`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `--max-parents=0` gives all root commits and `--min-parents=3` all octopus merges.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `--no-min-parents` and `--no-max-parents` reset these limits (to no limit) again.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Equivalent forms are `--min-parents=0` (any commit has 0 or more parents) and `--max-parents=-1` (negative numbers denote no upper limit).
[src:git/git-log-p02] When finding commits to include, follow only the first parent commit upon seeing a merge commit.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This option also changes default diff format for merge commits to `first-parent`, see `--diff-merges=first-parent` for details.
[src:git/git-log-p02] When finding commits to exclude (with a *^*), follow only the first parent commit upon seeing a merge commit.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This can be used to find the set of changes in a topic branch from the point where it diverged from the remote branch, given that arbitrary merges can be valid topic branch changes.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Restrict the output commits to be those that are not reachable from any other commits in the revision range.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Reverses the meaning of the *^* prefix (or lack thereof) for all following revision specifiers, up to the next `--not`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] When used on the command line before --stdin, the revisions passed through stdin will not be affected by it.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Conversely, when passed via standard input, the revisions passed on the command line will not be affected by it.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Pretend as if all the refs in `refs/`, along with `HEAD`, are listed on the command line as *<commit>*.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Pretend as if all the refs in `refs/heads` are listed on the command line as *<commit>*.
[src:git/git-log-p02] If *<pattern>* is given, limit branches to ones matching given shell glob.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Pretend as if all the refs in `refs/tags` are listed on the command line as *<commit>*.
[src:git/git-log-p02] If *<pattern>* is given, limit tags to ones matching given shell glob.
[src:git/git-log-p02] If pattern lacks *?*, ***, or *[*, */** at the end is implied.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Pretend as if all the refs in `refs/remotes` are listed on the command line as *<commit>*.
[src:git/git-log-p02] If *<pattern>* is given, limit remote-tracking branches to ones matching given shell glob.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Pretend as if all the refs matching shell glob *<glob-pattern>* are listed on the command line as *<commit>*.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Leading *refs/*, is automatically prepended if missing.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Do not include refs matching *<glob-pattern>* that the next `--all`, `--branches`, `--tags`, `--remotes`, or `--glob` would otherwise consider.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Repetitions of this option accumulate exclusion patterns up to the next `--all`, `--branches`, `--tags`, `--remotes`, or `--glob` option (other options or arguments do not clear accumulated patterns).
[src:git/git-log-p02] The patterns given should not begin with `refs/heads`, `refs/tags`, or `refs/remotes` when applied to `--branches`, `--tags`, or `--remotes`, respectively, and they must begin with `refs/` when applied to `--glob` or `--all`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] If a trailing */** is intended, it must be given explicitly.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Do not include refs that would be hidden by `git-fetch`, `git-receive-pack` or `git-upload-pack` by consulting the appropriate `fetch.hideRefs`, `receive.hideRefs` or `uploadpack.hideRefs` configuration along with `transfer.hideRefs` (see git-config[1]).
[src:git/git-log-p02] This option affects the next pseudo-ref option `--all` or `--glob` and is cleared after processing them.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Pretend as if all objects mentioned by reflogs are listed on the command line as *<commit>*.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Pretend as if all objects mentioned as ref tips of alternate repositories were listed on the command line.
[src:git/git-log-p02] An alternate repository is any repository whose object directory is specified in `objects/info/alternates`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] The set of included objects may be modified by `core.alternateRefsCommand`, etc.
[src:git/git-log-p02] By default, all working trees will be examined by the following options when there are more than one (see git-worktree[1]): `--all`, `--reflog` and `--indexed-objects`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This option forces them to examine the current working tree only.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Upon seeing an invalid object name in the input, pretend as if the bad input was not given.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Pretend as if the bad bisection ref `refs/bisect/bad` was listed and as if it was followed by `--not` and the good bisection refs `refs/bisect/good-*` on the command line.
[src:git/git-log-p02] In addition to getting arguments from the command line, read them from standard input as well.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This accepts commits and pseudo-options like `--all` and `--glob=`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] When a `--` separator is seen, the following input is treated as paths and used to limit the result.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Flags like `--not` which are read via standard input are only respected for arguments passed in the same way and will not influence any subsequent command line arguments.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Like `--cherry-pick` (see below) but mark equivalent commits with `=` rather than omitting them, and inequivalent ones with `+`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Omit any commit that introduces the same change as another commit on the “other side” when the set of commits are limited with symmetric difference.
[src:git/git-log-p02] For example, if you have two branches, `A` and `B`, a usual way to list all commits on only one side of them is with `--left-right` (see the example below in the description of the `--left-right` option).
[src:git/git-log-p02] However, it shows the commits that were cherry-picked from the other branch (for example, “3rd on b” may be cherry-picked from branch A).
[src:git/git-log-p02] With this option, such pairs of commits are excluded from the output.
[src:git/git-log-p02] List only commits on the respective side of a symmetric difference, i.e. only those which would be marked *<* resp.
[src:git/git-log-p02] For example, `--cherry-pick` `--right-only` `A...B` omits those commits from `B` which are in `A` or are patch-equivalent to a commit in `A`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] In other words, this lists the `+` commits from `git` `cherry` `A` `B`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] More precisely, `--cherry-pick` `--right-only` `--no-merges` gives the exact list.
[src:git/git-log-p02] A synonym for `--right-only` `--cherry-mark` `--no-merges`; useful to limit the output to the commits on our side and mark those that have been applied to the other side of a forked history with `git` `log` `--cherry` `upstream...mybranch`, similar to `git` `cherry` `upstream` `mybranch`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Instead of walking the commit ancestry chain, walk reflog entries from the most recent one to older ones.
[src:git/git-log-p02] When this option is used you cannot specify commits to exclude (that is, `^`*<commit>*, *<commit1>*`..`*<commit2>*, and *<commit1>*`...`*<commit2>* notations cannot be used).
[src:git/git-log-p02] With `--pretty` format other than `oneline` and `reference` (for obvious reasons), this causes the output to have two extra lines of information taken from the reflog.
[src:git/git-log-p02] If the starting point was specified as `ref@{now}`, show the timestamp format.
[src:git/git-log-p02] If neither was used, but `--date` was given on the command line, show the timestamp in the format requested by `--date`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Under `--pretty=oneline`, the commit message is prefixed with this information on the same line.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This option cannot be combined with `--reverse`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Under `--pretty=reference`, this information will not be shown at all.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Show commits touching conflicted paths in the range `HEAD...`*<other>*, where *<other>* is the first existing pseudoref in `MERGE_HEAD`, `CHERRY_PICK_HEAD`, `REVERT_HEAD` or `REBASE_HEAD`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Only works when the index has unmerged entries.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This option can be used to show relevant commits when resolving conflicts from a 3-way merge.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Sometimes you are only interested in parts of the history, for example the commits modifying a particular <path>.
[src:git/git-log-p02] But there are two parts of *History Simplification*, one part is selecting the commits and the other is how to do it, as there are various strategies to simplify the history.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Commits modifying the given <paths> are selected.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Commits that are referred by some branch or tag are selected.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Note that extra commits can be shown to give a meaningful history.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Simplifies the history to the simplest history explaining the final state of the tree.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Include all commits from the default mode, but also any merge commits that are not TREESAME to the first parent but are TREESAME to a later parent.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This mode is helpful for showing the merge commits that "first introduced" a change to a branch.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Same as the default mode, but does not prune some history.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Only the selected commits are shown, plus some to have a meaningful history.
[src:git/git-log-p02] All commits in the simplified history are shown.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Additional option to `--full-history` to remove some needless merges from the resulting history, as there are no selected commits contributing to this merge.
[src:git/git-log-p02] When given a range of commits to display (e.g.
[src:git/git-log-p02] *<commit1>*`..`*<commit2>* or *<commit2>* `^`*<commit1>*), and a commit *<commit>* in that range, only display commits in that range that are ancestors of *<commit>*, descendants of *<commit>*, or *<commit>* itself.
[src:git/git-log-p02] If no commit is specified, use *<commit1>* (the excluded part of the range) as *<commit>*.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Can be passed multiple times; if so, a commit is included if it is any of the commits given or if it is an ancestor or descendant of one of them.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Suppose you specified `foo` as the *<paths>*.
[src:git/git-log-p02] We shall call commits that modify `foo` !TREESAME, and the rest TREESAME.
[src:git/git-log-p02] In the following, we will always refer to the same example history to illustrate the differences between simplification settings.
[src:git/git-log-p02] The horizontal line of history A---Q is taken to be the first parent of each merge.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `rev-list` walks backwards through history, including or excluding commits based on whether `--full-history` and/or parent rewriting (via `--parents` or `--children`) are used.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Commits are included if they are not TREESAME to any parent (though this can be changed, see `--sparse` below).
[src:git/git-log-p02] If the commit was a merge, and it was TREESAME to one parent, follow only that parent.
[src:git/git-log-p02] (Even if there are several TREESAME parents, follow only one of them.) Otherwise, follow all parents.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Note how the rule to only follow the TREESAME parent, if one is available, removed `B` from consideration entirely.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `C` was considered via `N`, but is TREESAME.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Root commits are compared to an empty tree, so `I` is !TREESAME.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Parent/child relations are only visible with `--parents`, but that does not affect the commits selected in default mode, so we have shown the parent lines.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This mode differs from the default in one point: always follow all parents of a merge, even if it is TREESAME to one of them.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Even if more than one side of the merge has commits that are included, this does not imply that the merge itself is!
[src:git/git-log-p02] `M` was excluded because it is TREESAME to both parents.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `E`, `C` and `B` were all walked, but only `B` was !TREESAME, so the others do not appear.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Note that without parent rewriting, it is not really possible to talk about the parent/child relationships between the commits, so we show them disconnected.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Ordinary commits are only included if they are !TREESAME (though this can be changed, see `--sparse` below).
[src:git/git-log-p02] However, their parent list is rewritten: Along each parent, prune away commits that are not included themselves.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Compare to `--full-history` without rewriting above.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Note that `E` was pruned away because it is TREESAME, but the parent list of P was rewritten to contain `E`'s parent `I`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] The same happened for `C` and `N`, and `X`, `Y` and `Q`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Commits that are walked are included if they are not TREESAME to any parent.
[src:git/git-log-p02] All commits that are walked are included.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Note that without `--full-history`, this still simplifies merges: if one of the parents is TREESAME, we follow only that one, so the other sides of the merge are never walked.
[src:git/git-log-p02] First, build a history graph in the same way that `--full-history` with parent rewriting does (see above).
[src:git/git-log-p02] The effect of this is best shown by way of comparing to `--full-history` with parent rewriting.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Limit the displayed commits to those which are an ancestor of *<commit>*, or which are a descendant of *<commit>*, or are *<commit>* itself.
[src:git/git-log-p02] A regular *D..M* computes the set of commits that are ancestors of `M`, but excludes the ones that are ancestors of `D`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This is useful to see what happened to the history leading to `M` since `D`, in the sense that "what does `M` have that did not exist in `D`".
[src:git/git-log-p02] The result in this example would be all the commits, except `A` and `B` (and `D` itself, of course).
[src:git/git-log-p02] When we want to find out what commits in `M` are contaminated with the bug introduced by `D` and need fixing, however, we might want to view only the subset of `D..M` that are actually descendants of `D`, i.e. excluding `C` and `K`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This is exactly what the `--ancestry-path` option does.
[src:git/git-log-p02] We can also use `--ancestry-path=D` instead of `--ancestry-path` which means the same thing when applied to the `D..M` range but is just more explicit.
[src:git/git-log-p02] If we instead are interested in a given topic within this range, and all commits affected by that topic, we may only want to view the subset of `D..M` which contain that topic in their ancestry path.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Before discussing another option, `--show-pulls`, we need to create a new example history.
[src:git/git-log-p02] A common problem users face when looking at simplified history is that a commit they know changed a file somehow does not appear in the file’s simplified history.
[src:git/git-log-p02] For this example, suppose `I` created `file.txt` which was modified by `A`, `B`, and `X` in different ways.
[src:git/git-log-p02] The single-parent commits `C`, `Z`, and `Y` do not change `file.txt`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] The merge commit `M` was created by resolving the merge conflict to include both changes from `A` and `B` and hence is not TREESAME to either.
[src:git/git-log-p02] The merge commit `R`, however, was created by ignoring the contents of `file.txt` at `M` and taking only the contents of `file.txt` at `X`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Hence, `R` is TREESAME to `X` but not `M`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Finally, the natural merge resolution to create `N` is to take the contents of `file.txt` at `R`, so `N` is TREESAME to `R` but not `C`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] The merge commits `O` and `P` are TREESAME to their first parents, but not to their second parents, `Z` and `Y` respectively.
[src:git/git-log-p02] When using the default mode, `N` and `R` both have a TREESAME parent, so those edges are walked and the others are ignored.
[src:git/git-log-p02] When using `--full-history`, Git walks every edge.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This will discover the commits `A` and `B` and the merge `M`, but also will reveal the merge commits `O` and `P`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Here, the merge commits `O` and `P` contribute extra noise, as they did not actually contribute a change to `file.txt`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] They only merged a topic that was based on an older version of `file.txt`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This is a common issue in repositories using a workflow where many contributors work in parallel and merge their topic branches along a single trunk: many unrelated merges appear in the `--full-history` results.
[src:git/git-log-p02] When using the `--simplify-merges` option, the commits `O` and `P` disappear from the results.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This is because the rewritten second parents of `O` and `P` are reachable from their first parents.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Those edges are removed and then the commits look like single-parent commits that are TREESAME to their parent.
[src:git/git-log-p02] In this view, we see all of the important single-parent changes from `A`, `B`, and `X`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] We also see the carefully-resolved merge `M` and the not-so-carefully-resolved merge `R`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This is usually enough information to determine why the commits `A` and `B` "disappeared" from history in the default view.
[src:git/git-log-p02] However, there are a few issues with this approach.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Unlike any previous option, the `--simplify-merges` option requires walking the entire commit history before returning a single result.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This can make the option difficult to use for very large repositories.
[src:git/git-log-p02] When many contributors are working on the same repository, it is important which merge commits introduced a change into an important branch.
[src:git/git-log-p02] The problematic merge `R` above is not likely to be the merge commit that was used to merge into an important branch.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Instead, the merge `N` was used to merge `R` and `X` into the important branch.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This commit may have information about why the change `X` came to override the changes from `A` and `B` in its commit message.
[src:git/git-log-p02] In addition to the commits shown in the default history, show each merge commit that is not TREESAME to its first parent but is TREESAME to a later parent.
[src:git/git-log-p02] When a merge commit is included by `--show-pulls`, the merge is treated as if it "pulled" the change from another branch.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Here, the merge commits `R` and `N` are included because they pulled the commits `X` and `R` into the base branch, respectively.
[src:git/git-log-p02] These merges are the reason the commits `A` and `B` do not appear in the default history.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Notice that since `M` is reachable from `R`, the edge from `N` to `M` was simplified away.
[src:git/git-log-p02] However, `N` still appears in the history as an important commit because it "pulled" the change `R` into the main branch.
[src:git/git-log-p02] The `--simplify-by-decoration` option allows you to view only the big picture of the topology of the history, by omitting commits that are not referenced by tags.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Commits are marked as !TREESAME (in other words, kept after history simplification rules described above) if (1) they are referenced by tags, or (2) they change the contents of the paths given on the command line.
[src:git/git-log-p02] All other commits are marked as TREESAME (subject to be simplified away).
[src:git/git-log-p02] By default, the commits are shown in reverse chronological order.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Show no parents before all of its children are shown, but otherwise show commits in the commit timestamp order.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Show no parents before all of its children are shown, but otherwise show commits in the author timestamp order.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Show no parents before all of its children are shown, and avoid showing commits on multiple lines of history intermixed.
[src:git/git-log-p02] where the numbers denote the order of commit timestamps, `git` `rev-list` and friends with `--date-order` show the commits in the timestamp order: 8 7 6 5 4 3 2 1.
[src:git/git-log-p02] With `--topo-order`, they would show 8 6 5 3 7 4 2 1 (or 8 7 4 2 6 5 3 1); some older commits are shown before newer ones in order to avoid showing the commits from two parallel development track mixed together.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Output the commits chosen to be shown (see *Commit Limiting* section above) in reverse order.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Cannot be combined with `--walk-reflogs`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] These options are mostly targeted for packing of Git repositories.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Only show the given commits, but do not traverse their ancestors.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This has no effect if a range is specified.
[src:git/git-log-p02] If the argument `unsorted` is given, the commits are shown in the order they were given on the command line.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Otherwise (if `sorted` or no argument was given), the commits are shown in reverse chronological order by commit time.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Pretty-print the contents of the commit logs in a given format, where *<format>* can be one of `oneline`, `short`, `medium`, `full`, `fuller`, `reference`, `email`, `raw`, `format:`*<string>* and `tformat:`*<string>*.
[src:git/git-log-p02] When *<format>* is none of the above, and has `%`*<placeholder>* in it, it acts as if `--pretty=tformat:`*<format>* were given.
[src:git/git-log-p02] See the "PRETTY FORMATS" section for some additional details for each format.
[src:git/git-log-p02] When `=`*<format>* part is omitted, it defaults to `medium`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Instead of showing the full 40-byte hexadecimal commit object name, show a prefix that names the object uniquely.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `--abbrev=`*<n>* (which also modifies diff output, if it is displayed) option can be used to specify the minimum length of the prefix.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This should make `--pretty=oneline` a whole lot more readable for people using 80-column terminals.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Show the full 40-byte hexadecimal commit object name.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This negates `--abbrev-commit`, either explicit or implied by other options such as `--oneline`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] It also overrides the `log.abbrevCommit` variable.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This is a shorthand for `--pretty=oneline` `--abbrev-commit` used together.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Commit objects record the character encoding used for the log message in their encoding header; this option can be used to tell the command to re-code the commit log message in the encoding preferred by the user.
[src:git/git-log-p02] For non plumbing commands this defaults to UTF-8.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Note that if an object claims to be encoded in `X` and we are outputting in `X`, we will output the object verbatim; this means that invalid sequences in the original commit may be copied to the output.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Likewise, if iconv(3) fails to convert the commit, we will quietly output the original object verbatim.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Perform a tab expansion (replace each tab with enough spaces to fill to the next display column that is a multiple of *<n>*) in the log message before showing it in the output.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `--expand-tabs` is a short-hand for `--expand-tabs=8`, and `--no-expand-tabs` is a short-hand for `--expand-tabs=0`, which disables tab expansion.
[src:git/git-log-p02] By default, tabs are expanded in pretty formats that indent the log message by 4 spaces (i.e.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `medium`, which is the default, `full`, and `fuller`).
[src:git/git-log-p02] Show the notes (see git-notes[1]) that annotate the commit, when showing the commit log message.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This is the default for `git` `log`, `git` `show` and `git` `whatchanged` commands when there is no `--pretty`, `--format`, or `--oneline` option given on the command line.
[src:git/git-log-p02] By default, the notes shown are from the notes refs listed in the `core.notesRef` and `notes.displayRef` variables (or corresponding environment overrides).
[src:git/git-log-p02] With an optional *<ref>* argument, use the ref to find the notes to display.
[src:git/git-log-p02] The ref can specify the full refname when it begins with `refs/notes/`; when it begins with `notes/`, `refs/` and otherwise `refs/notes/` is prefixed to form the full name of the ref.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Multiple `--notes` options can be combined to control which notes are being displayed.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Examples: "`--notes=foo`" will show only notes from `refs/notes/foo`; "`--notes=foo` `--notes`" will show both notes from "refs/notes/foo" and from the default notes ref(s).
[src:git/git-log-p02] This negates the above `--notes` option, by resetting the list of notes refs from which notes are shown.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Options are parsed in the order given on the command line, so e.g.
[src:git/git-log-p02] "`--notes` `--notes=foo` `--no-notes` `--notes=bar`" will only show notes from `refs/notes/bar`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Show the default notes unless options for displaying specific notes are given.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Use the above `--notes`/`--no-notes` options instead.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Check the validity of a signed commit object by passing the signature to `gpg` `--verify` and show the output.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Only takes effect for dates shown in human-readable format, such as when using `--pretty`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `log.date` config variable sets a default value for the log command’s `--date` option.
[src:git/git-log-p02] By default, dates are shown in the original time zone (either committer’s or author’s).
[src:git/git-log-p02] If `-local` is appended to the format (e.g., `iso-local`), the user’s local time zone is used instead.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `--date=relative` shows dates relative to the current time, e.g. “2 hours ago”.
[src:git/git-log-p02] The `-local` option has no effect for `--date=relative`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `--date=local` is an alias for `--date=default-local`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `--date=iso-strict` (or `--date=iso8601-strict`) shows timestamps in strict ISO 8601 format.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `--date=rfc` (or `--date=rfc2822`) shows timestamps in RFC 2822 format, often found in email messages.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `--date=short` shows only the date, but not the time, in `YYYY-MM-DD` format.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `--date=raw` shows the date as seconds since the epoch (1970-01-01 00:00:00 UTC), followed by a space, and then the timezone as an offset from UTC (a `+` or `-` with four digits; the first two are hours, and the second two are minutes).
[src:git/git-log-p02] I.e., as if the timestamp were formatted with `strftime`(`"%s` `%z"`)).
[src:git/git-log-p02] Note that the `-local` option does not affect the seconds-since-epoch value (which is always measured in UTC), but does switch the accompanying timezone value.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `--date=human` shows the timezone if the timezone does not match the current time-zone, and doesn’t print the whole date if that matches (ie skip printing year for dates that are "this year", but also skip the whole date itself if it’s in the last few days and we can just say what weekday it was).
[src:git/git-log-p02] For older dates the hour and minute is also omitted.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `--date=unix` shows the date as a Unix epoch timestamp (seconds since 1970).
[src:git/git-log-p02] As with `--raw`, this is always in UTC and therefore `-local` has no effect.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `--date=format:`*<format>* feeds the *<format>* to your system `strftime`, except for `%s`, `%z`, and `%Z`, which are handled internally.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Use `--date=format:%c` to show the date in your system locale’s preferred format.
[src:git/git-log-p02] See the `strftime`(3) manual for a complete list of format placeholders.
[src:git/git-log-p02] When using `-local`, the correct syntax is `--date=format-local:`*<format>*.
[src:git/git-log-p02] `--date=default` is the default format, and is based on ctime(3) output.
[src:git/git-log-p02] It shows a single line with three-letter day of the week, three-letter month, day-of-month, hour-minute-seconds in "HH:MM:SS" format, followed by 4-digit year, plus timezone information, unless the local time zone is used, e.g.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Print also the parents of the commit (in the form "commit parent…").
[src:git/git-log-p02] Also enables parent rewriting, see *History Simplification* above.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Print also the children of the commit (in the form "commit child…").
[src:git/git-log-p02] Mark which side of a symmetric difference a commit is reachable from.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Commits from the left side are prefixed with *<* and those from the right with *>*.
[src:git/git-log-p02] If combined with `--boundary`, those commits are prefixed with `-`.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Draw a text-based graphical representation of the commit history on the left hand side of the output.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This may cause extra lines to be printed in between commits, in order for the graph history to be drawn properly.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This enables parent rewriting, see *History Simplification* above.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This implies the `--topo-order` option by default, but the `--date-order` option may also be specified.
[src:git/git-log-p02] When `--graph` is not used, all history branches are flattened which can make it hard to see that the two consecutive commits do not belong to a linear branch.
[src:git/git-log-p02] This option puts a barrier in between them in that case.
[src:git/git-log-p02] If *<barrier>* is specified, it is the string that will be shown instead of the default one.
[src:git/git-log-p02] When `--graph` is used, limit the number of graph lanes to be shown.
[src:git/git-log-p02] Lanes over the limit are replaced with a truncation mark *~*.
[src:git/git-log-p02] By default it is set to 0 (no limit), zero and negative values are ignored and treated as no limit.
[src:git/git-log-p03] If the commit is a merge, and if the pretty-format is not `oneline`, `email` or `raw`, an additional line is inserted before the `Author:` line.
[src:git/git-log-p03] This line begins with "Merge: " and the hashes of ancestral commits are printed, separated by spaces.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Note that the listed commits may not necessarily be the list of the *direct* parent commits if you have limited your view of history: for example, if you are only interested in changes related to a certain directory or file.
[src:git/git-log-p03] There are several built-in formats, and you can define additional formats by setting a pretty.<name> config option to either another format name, or a `format:` string, as described below (see git-config[1]).
[src:git/git-log-p03] This is designed to be as compact as possible.
[src:git/git-log-p03] This format is used to refer to another commit in a commit message and is the same as `--pretty='format:%C`(`auto`)`%h` (`%s,` `%ad`).
[src:git/git-log-p03] By default, the date is formatted with `--date=short` unless another `--date` option is explicitly specified.
[src:git/git-log-p03] As with any `format:` with format placeholders, its output is not affected by other options like `--decorate` and `--walk-reflogs`.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Like `email`, but lines in the commit message starting with "From " (preceded by zero or more ">") are quoted with ">" so they aren’t confused as starting a new commit.
[src:git/git-log-p03] The `raw` format shows the entire commit exactly as stored in the commit object.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Notably, the hashes are displayed in full, regardless of whether `--abbrev` or `--no-abbrev` are used, and *parents* information show the true parent commits, without taking grafts or history simplification into account.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Note that this format affects the way commits are displayed, but not the way the diff is shown e.g. with `git` `log` `--raw`.
[src:git/git-log-p03] To get full object names in a raw diff format, use `--no-abbrev`.
[src:git/git-log-p03] The `format:`*<format-string>* format allows you to specify which information you want to show.
[src:git/git-log-p03] It works a little bit like printf format, with the notable exception that you get a newline with `%n` instead of *\n*.
[src:git/git-log-p03] The `tformat:` format works exactly like `format:`, except that it provides "terminator" semantics instead of "separator" semantics.
[src:git/git-log-p03] In other words, each commit has the message terminator character (usually a newline) appended, rather than a separator placed between entries.
[src:git/git-log-p03] This means that the final entry of a single-line format will be properly terminated with a new line, just as the "oneline" format does.
[src:git/git-log-p03] In addition, any unrecognized string that has a `%` in it is interpreted as if it has `tformat:` in front of it.
[src:git/git-log-p03] By default, `git` `log` does not generate any diff output.
[src:git/git-log-p03] The options below can be used to show the changes made by each commit.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Note that unless one of `--diff-merges` variants (including short `-m`, `-c`, `--cc`, and `--dd` options) is explicitly given, merge commits will not show a diff, even if a diff format like `--patch` is selected, nor will they match search options like `-S`.
[src:git/git-log-p03] The exception is when `--first-parent` is in use, in which case `first-parent` is the default format for merge commits.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Show diffs for merge commits in the default format.
[src:git/git-log-p03] This is similar to `--diff-merges=on`, except `-m` will produce no output unless `-p` is given as well.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Produce combined diff output for merge commits.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Shortcut for `--diff-merges=combined` `-p`.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Produce dense combined diff output for merge commits.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Shortcut for `--diff-merges=dense-combined` `-p`.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Produce diff with respect to first parent for both merge and regular commits.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Shortcut for `--diff-merges=first-parent` `-p`.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Produce remerge-diff output for merge commits.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Shortcut for `--diff-merges=remerge` `-p`.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Specify diff format to be used for merge commits.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Default is `off` unless `--first-parent` is in use, in which case `first-parent` is the default.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Disable output of diffs for merge commits.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Make diff output for merge commits to be shown in the default format.
[src:git/git-log-p03] The default format can be changed using `log.diffMerges` configuration variable, whose default value is `separate`.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Show full diff with respect to first parent.
[src:git/git-log-p03] This is the same format as `--patch` produces for non-merge commits.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Show full diff with respect to each of parents.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Separate log entry and diff is generated for each parent.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Show differences from each of the parents to the merge result simultaneously instead of showing pairwise diff between a parent and the result one at a time.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Furthermore, it lists only files which were modified from all parents.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Further compress output produced by `--diff-merges=combined` by omitting uninteresting hunks whose contents in the parents have only two variants and the merge result picks one of them without modification.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Remerge two-parent merge commits to create a temporary tree object—potentially containing files with conflict markers and such.
[src:git/git-log-p03] A diff is then shown between that temporary tree and the actual merge commit.
[src:git/git-log-p03] The output emitted when this option is used is subject to change, and so is its interaction with other options (unless explicitly documented).
[src:git/git-log-p03] Cause combined diffs (used for merge commits) to list the name of the file from all parents.
[src:git/git-log-p03] It thus only has effect when `--diff-merges=`[`dense-`]`combined` is in use, and is likely only useful if filename changes are detected (i.e. when either rename or copy detection have been requested).
[src:git/git-log-p03] For each commit, show a summary of changes using the raw diff format.
[src:git/git-log-p03] See the "RAW OUTPUT FORMAT" section of git-diff[1].
[src:git/git-log-p03] This is different from showing the log itself in raw format, which you can achieve with `--format=raw`.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Show the tree objects in the diff output.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Separate the commits with *NUL*s instead of newlines.
[src:git/git-log-p03] Also, when `--raw` or `--numstat` has been given, do not munge pathnames and use *NUL*s as output field terminators.
[src:git/git-log-p03] If generating diffs, detect and report renames for each commit.
[src:git/git-log-p03] For following files across renames while traversing history, see `--follow`.
[src:git/git-log-p04] Show the changes during the last two weeks to the file `gitk`.
[src:git/git-log-p04] Show the commits that are in the "`test`" branch but not yet in the "`release`" branch, along with the list of paths each commit modifies.
[src:git/git-log-p04] Shows the commits that changed `builtin/rev-list.c`, including those commits that occurred before the file was given its present name.
[src:git/git-log-p04] Shows all commits that are in any of local branches but not in any of remote-tracking branches for `origin` (what you have that origin doesn’t).
[src:git/git-log-p04] Shows all commits that are in local master but not in any remote repository master branches.
[src:git/git-log-p04] Shows the history including change diffs, but only from the “main branch” perspective, skipping commits that come from merged branches, and showing full diffs of changes introduced by the merges.
[src:git/git-log-p04] This makes sense only when following a strict policy of merging all topic branches when staying on a single integration branch.
[src:git/git-log-p04] Shows how the function `main`() in the file `main.c` evolved over time.
[src:git/git-log-p04] Limits the number of commits to show to 3.
[src:git/git-log-p04] See git-config[1] for core variables and git-diff[1] for settings related to diff generation.
[src:git/git-log-p04] (See *Pretty Formats* above.) Defaults to `medium`.
[src:git/git-log-p04] (See *Discussion* above.) Defaults to the value of `i18n.commitEncoding` if set, and UTF-8 otherwise.
[src:git/git-log-p04] If `true`, make git-log[1], git-show[1], and git-whatchanged[1] assume `--abbrev-commit`.
